<DOC><DOCNO> AP890330-0224 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-89 1140EST</FILEID><FIRST>d f BC-OAPEC-Refining     03-30 0223</FIRST><SECOND>BC-OAPEC-Refining,0232</SECOND><HEAD>OAPEC Needs More Capital For New Refineries</HEAD><DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Organization of Arab Petroleum ExportingCountries urged its member states Thursday to invest in oilrefining industries to meet new trends in world demand for oilproducts.   An OAPEC statement issued at the end of a three-day seminar onthe Arab refining industry, affirmed ``the need to directinvestment toward building new refining units in the Arab countriesthat can process heavy high-sulphur Arab crudes and handle surplusfuel oil.''   Such investement ``will increase the marketing potential of Arabproducers, since these crudes constitute a large portion of theiroil reserves,'' the statement said.   More than 100 delegates and oil experts from Arab countries,regional and international companies and organizations, includingthe Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries, attended themeeting.   The Kuwait-based 11-member OAPEC, in which seven countriesdouble as members of OPEC, provides a forum for coordinating Araboil policies.   OAPEC members are: Kuwait, Saudi Arabia, Qatar, the United ArabEmirates, Iraq, Algeria, Libya, Bahrain, Syria, Tunisia and Egypt.The first seven are OPEC members.   The participants noted the share of light products in the totaldemand for oil was growing steadily and that there is a trendtoward eliminating pollutants such as sulphur and lead from oilproducts in line with new environmental regulations in majormarkets.</TEXT></DOC>